# Object parameters only (outside repositories)

Every function and method we author in `src/**/*.ts` MUST accept its inputs as a **single named options object** when it has two or more parameters. This rule applies across the whole codebase except for repositories and their unit tests.

## Exempt files (positional parameters allowed)

- `**/*.repository.ts` — repositories are the data-access seam; their signatures stay aligned with Drizzle/SQL helpers. Positional params (`findById(id)`, `findByUserAndOrganization(userId, organizationId)`) are explicitly allowed.
- `**/*.repository.unit.test.ts` — repository unit tests mirror repository signatures and stay positional to match.

## Exempt signatures (positional parameters required by the framework)

These call shapes are dictated by third-party libraries; do not force object params on them:

- **Fastify route/middleware callbacks** — `(request, reply)`, `(request, reply, payload)`, `(error, request, reply)`. Plugin factories such as `(app, options) => ...` follow Fastify’s pattern.
- **BullMQ worker processors** — `(job)`, `(job, token)`, `(job, error)` callbacks passed to `new Worker(...)` or as listeners.
- **Class constructors used for DI** — `constructor(repository, service, ...)` in `*.container.ts` and the service/worker classes wired by it. Container plumbing stays positional.
- **Event-bus subscribers / emitters** — `eventBus.on(eventType, handler)`, `eventBus.emit(eventType, payload)`.
- **Node and standard callbacks** — `Array.prototype.sort/reduce/map` comparators, `setTimeout(callback, ms)`, EventEmitter `(event, listener)`, `pipe(a, b, c)`-style composition.
- **Test framework callbacks** — `describe(name, fn)`, `it(name, fn)`, `beforeEach(fn)`, `vi.fn(impl)`, `expect(value).toEqual(expected)` and similar matcher arguments. Inline `vi.mock('mod', factory)` factories also stay positional.
- **Zod / drizzle DSL** — `.refine((value, ctx) => ...)`, `.superRefine((value, ctx) => ...)`, `sql\`${a} = ${b}\``. Schema builders are not application code.

If a wrapper of one of the above signatures is authored by us (e.g. our own `withRequestContext(handler)` helper), the wrapper itself follows the framework signature; only the wrapped business function must take an object.

## Required form

For two or more parameters, prefer a named input interface that lives next to the function:

```ts
// Good — services, controllers, validators, serializers, workers, queues, utilities, etc.
export interface CreateOrganizationInput {
  ownerUserId: number;
  name: string;
  plan?: string;
}

async function createOrganization(input: CreateOrganizationInput): Promise<Organization> {
  // ...
}

await organizationService.createOrganization({ ownerUserId, name, plan: 'pro' });
```

Inline destructuring is acceptable when the shape is small, local, and not re-used:

```ts
export function buildAuditFilters({ from, to, action }: { from?: Date; to?: Date; action?: string }) {
  // ...
}
```

Single-parameter functions are unaffected:

```ts
export function serializeOrganization(row: OrganizationRow): OrganizationOutput { ... }
async function findByPublicId(public_id: string): Promise<UserRow | null> { ... }
```

## What this rule explicitly forbids in non-exempt files

1. Two or more positional parameters that are not part of an exempt framework signature.
   - Bad: `async function listForUser(user_public_id: string, limit: number, includeTotal: boolean)`
   - Good: `async function listForUser(user_public_id: string, options: NotificationListServiceOptions)` (one scalar identity + one options bag is still considered “object params” because the second argument carries every choice).
2. Boolean positional flags. Always pass `{ enabled: true }`, never `setX(true)`.
3. Optional positional “tail” parameters (e.g. `(public_id, query?, options?, signal?)`) — collapse them into one options object.

When converting existing code, also accept the “identity + options” shape (`(public_id, options)`): a primary identity argument followed by one options object is fine because the identity stays unambiguous and the rest of the inputs travel together.

## When you touch existing code

- If you are editing a function that already violates this rule **and your change is non-trivial**, refactor the signature to an options object and update all call sites in the same diff.
- Cosmetic / one-line edits do not require a full refactor; leave a follow-up TODO comment instead.
- Do not refactor exempt files. Repositories and framework-callback files stay as-is.

